def AR_fit(x, p):
    """
    Estimate the parameters of an Auto-regressive (AR) model 
    of order p on a scalar time series x.
    
    Parameters:
    -----------
    x: np.array shape=(T,)
        Scalar valued time series.
    p: int
        Order of the AR process.

    Returns:
    --------
    coef: np.array shape=(p,)
        Coefficient estimates of the AR(p) model.
    """
    T = len(x)
    y = x[p:] # target vector

    # Regressor matrix
    X = np.zeros((T-p, p+1))    # pre-allocation
    X[:,0] = 1                  # absorbing intercept by a column of ones.
    for i in range(1, p+1):
        X[:,i] = x[p-i:T-i]     # building the regressor matrix

    # Linear regression.
    reg = LinearRegression().fit(X, y)
    return reg.coef_
In [4]:
# Coefficient estimation of AR(1) model on raw data.
print(AR_fit(data1, 1))

[0.         0.99702754]

We obtain a coefficient estimate $a_1 \sim 1$, which is very close to the threshold for divergence (sufficient condition $|a_1|>1$ for divergence of an AR process). When $a_1 = 1$ the process is a random walk, which is what we can visually see in our time series. I was however expecting that we would have $a_0 \neq 0$ since we have a steady increasing trend in our TS. Not sure if this is due to an incorrect implementation by me, or if I haven't fully understood the thoery.

def AR1_step(x0, coef):
    """
    Take a single AR(1) step.
    """
    return coef.dot(np.array([1, x0])) + np.random.normal()

def stepping(n_steps, method, x0, coef):
    """
    Step n_steps into the future following the select method.
    """
    x = x0
    for i in range(n_steps):
        x = method(x0, coef)
    return x
In [10]:
def future_stepping(x, n_steps, method, coef):
    """
    Estimating n_steps future steps following an AR(p) model, starting at each timestep
    from true inital data. Calculates and returns the total squared residual average.
    """
    # Organisation and pre-allocation.
    x_init    = x[:-n_steps]
    x_truth   = x[n_steps:]
    x_predict = np.zeros_like(x_init)

    # For each timestep, estimate n_steps into the future.
    for i in range(len(x_init)):
        x_predict[i] = stepping(n_steps, method, x_init[i], coef)

    # Calculate squared residual average.
    residual = np.mean((x_predict - x_truth)**2)
    return residual, x_truth, x_predict

def return_plot_data(x, order):
    """
    Generate x and y data for an n:th order return plot.
    """
    x_out = x[:-order]
    y_out = x[order:]
    
    plt.scatter(x_out, y_out, s=10, alpha=0.25)
    plt.xlabel(f'$x_{{t-{order}}}$')
    plt.ylabel('$x_{t}$')
    if order%10 == 1:
        plt.title(f'{order}st order return')
    elif order%10 == 2:
        plt.title(f'{order}nd order return')
    elif order%10 == 3:
        plt.title(f'{order}rd order return')
    else: 
        plt.title(f'{order}th order return')
    plt.show()

def acorr(x, lags):
    """
    Determines auto-correlation for a time series x over sweep
    of time-lags in interval [0, lags).
    """
    acorr_arr = np.zeros(lags)    
    for i in range(lags):
        # Relative time shift
        if i > 0:
            x1 = x[:-i]
            x2 = x[i:]
        else:
            x1 = x
            x2 = x
        gamma_x1_x2  = ((x1-x1.mean())*(x2-x2.mean())).mean() # xcov(x1, x2)
        std_x1       = np.sqrt(((x1-x1.mean())**2).mean())    # std(x1)
        std_x2       = np.sqrt(((x2-x2.mean())**2).mean())    # std(x2)
        acorr_arr[i] = gamma_x1_x2 / (std_x1 * std_x2)        # acorr(x) = xcorr(x1,x2)
    # Plotting.
    plt.plot(acorr_arr, '-o')
    plt.title('Autocorrelation')
    plt.xlabel('Time-lag')
    plt.show()
In [24]:
acorr(x_MA, 30) # Moving average process.

def pacorr(x, lags):
    """
    Determines partial auto-correlation for a time series x over sweep
    of time-lags in interval [0, lags).
    """
    pacorr_arr = np.zeros(lags)    
    for i in range(lags):
        # Relative time shift.
        if i > 0:
            x1 = x[:-i].copy()
            x2 = x[i:].copy()
        else:
            x1 = x.copy()
            x2 = x.copy()
            
        if i > 1:
            # We have intermediate lags between x1 and x2. Find their linear dependence on x1 and x2.
            # Form a matrix X with concatenations of the intermediate lags for the TS.
            X = np.zeros((len(x1), i-1))
            for idx, j in enumerate(range(1, i)):
                X[:, idx] = x[j:-i+j]
            reg1 = LinearRegression().fit(X, x1) # Linear fit of intermediate lags to x1.
            reg2 = LinearRegression().fit(X, x2) # Linear fit of intermediate lags to x2.        
            x1 -= reg1.predict(X) # Remove linear dependence on the intermediate lags.
            x2 -= reg2.predict(X)
            
        # Calculate the autocorrelation.
        gamma_x1_x2  = ((x1-x1.mean())*(x2-x2.mean())).mean() # xcov(x1, x2)
        std_x1       = np.sqrt(((x1-x1.mean())**2).mean())    # std(x1)
        std_x2       = np.sqrt(((x2-x2.mean())**2).mean())    # std(x2)
        pacorr_arr[i] = gamma_x1_x2 / (std_x1 * std_x2)        # acorr(x) = xcorr(x1,x2)
        
    # Plotting.
    plt.plot(pacorr_arr, '-o')
    plt.title('Partial auto-correlation')
    plt.xlabel('Time-lag')
    plt.show()
In [27]:
pacorr(x_AR, 30) # Auto-regressive process.
